ANTHRAX - USA: FINGERPRINT QUESTIONS
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 21 Oct 2001
From: Patrick L. McDonough <plm2@cornell.edu> [edited]

Could you explain how the different worldwide anthrax strains are
differentiated? Is there a certain part of the _Bacillus anthracis_
genome that is "fingerprinted" in order to do this?
What is the technique used to accomplish this feat, e.g., RAPD-PCR, or
ribotyping?
How would a terrorist have acquired the "Ames strain" used in the
attacks?
What is the difference between the "Ames strain or strains" and the
vaccine strain called "Sterne"?
The strain used in the human vaccine made by Bioport is apparently
only different from field strains in that it lacks a capsule....and
the vaccine is made from the Protective Antigen (PA) obtained from
this strain? Is the same seed stock used to make the human subunit
vaccine also used to make the "live" spore suspension used in cattle
vaccines?
Is the seed stock for any of these vaccines believed to be the culprit
in the bioterrorist attacks? If that is correct I guess that tells me
that the seed stock is not avirulent for humans? ...or at least if
you put its spores up someone's nose that route makes it more
virulent?
If you could help me to understand the answers to these questions, I
would really appreciate the help! I am getting a lot of questions
from veterinarians about these issues.
­­
Dr. Patrick L. McDonough MS, PhD (Pat)
<plm2@dcornell.edu>
Acting Director - Bacteriology/Mycology Section
